---
import HiddenGrammarLayout from '../../layouts/HiddenGrammarLayout.astro';
---

<HiddenGrammarLayout
  title="Basquiat Holds. Kinkade Resolves."
  description="Two structural decisions every work makes: whether it holds or resolves, and how close it stays to the visible world."
>
  <div class="hg-page poles-page">

    <nav class="hg-breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/hidden-grammar">Art Lab</a>
      <span class="hg-breadcrumb-sep">›</span>
      <span>The 4 Poles</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="poles-header">
      <p class="poles-eyebrow">Framework Reference</p>
      <h1>Basquiat Holds. Kinkade Resolves.</h1>
      <p class="poles-subtitle">Two structural decisions. Every visual work sits somewhere on both axes, whether the artist knew it or not.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="poles-body">

      <p>Think about the last time you stood in front of a painting that made you uncomfortable. Not because something was wrong with it. Because it wouldn't give you what you came for. You kept waiting for it to resolve—to land somewhere, to let you go—and it never did. You left still carrying it.</p>

      <p>That's not an accident. That's a structural decision, whether the artist made it consciously or not. The work was built to hold tension, not release it. And here's where it gets interesting: most artists think they're choosing between finished and unfinished. They're not. They're choosing—usually without knowing it—whether the work holds or lets go. Those are different things entirely. A work can be completely finished and still refuse to resolve. That refusal is a position. So is its opposite: work that moves the viewer toward closure, toward rest, toward the feeling that something has been set right.</p>

      <p>Neither is better. But they're not the same, and confusing one for the other is how you end up with work that intends to disturb and instead soothes—or intends to comfort and instead unsettles.</p>

      <!-- Axis 1: Holds vs. Resolves -->
      <section class="poles-axis">
        <h2 class="poles-axis-label">Axis 1 — Holds vs. Resolves</h2>
        <p class="poles-axis-desc">Basquiat holds. Kinkade resolves. Neither makes the other wrong—but they are structurally opposite, and most of the friction in responding to work like Basquiat's comes from expecting a resolution that was never coming.</p>
        <div class="poles-pair">
          <div class="poles-card">
            <div class="poles-img-wrap">
              <img
                src="/images/poles/960px-Caspar_David_Friedrich_-_Wanderer_above_the_Sea_of_Fog.jpeg"
                alt="Caspar David Friedrich, Wanderer above the Sea of Fog, 1818"
                class="poles-img"
              />
              <p class="poles-img-caption">Caspar David Friedrich — <em>Wanderer above the Sea of Fog</em>, 1818</p>
            </div>
            <div class="poles-card-text">
              <h3 class="poles-pole-name">Holds</h3>
              <p>Tension is the point. The work opens something and leaves it open. Friedrich's wanderer stands at the edge of everything visible and looks into obscurity—the painting doesn't resolve that situation, it inhabits it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="poles-card">
            <div class="poles-img-wrap">
              <img
                src="/images/poles/960px-Raphael_-_Madonna_in_the_Meadow_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg"
                alt="Raphael, Madonna in the Meadow, 1506"
                class="poles-img"
              />
              <p class="poles-img-caption">Raphael — <em>Madonna in the Meadow</em>, 1506</p>
            </div>
            <div class="poles-card-text">
              <h3 class="poles-pole-name">Resolves</h3>
              <p>The work moves toward closure. Raphael's compositions feel complete not because they're simple, but because every formal element—weight, gaze, geometry—points toward rest. You can leave.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <p>The second question is quieter but just as structural: how close does this work stay to the visible world? Not whether it's "abstract" in the art world sense—that's a style category, not a structural one. The real question is whether the work refers directly to things you can recognize, or whether it has moved away from depiction toward something more generalized. That distance is a commitment. It determines what the viewer's eye can do, what the work can ask of them, and what it can deliver.</p>

      <!-- Axis 2: Close vs. Moved Away -->
      <section class="poles-axis">
        <h2 class="poles-axis-label">Axis 2 — Close to the visible world vs. Moved away from it</h2>
        <p class="poles-axis-desc">Dürer stays inside the visible world so precisely that you feel the fur. Kandinsky has left it almost entirely—what you track are forces, not things. Both are valid positions. But they ask entirely different things of the viewer's eye.</p>
        <div class="poles-pair">
          <div class="poles-card">
            <div class="poles-img-wrap">
              <img
                src="/images/poles/1280px-Albrecht_Dürer_-_Hare,_1502_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg"
                alt="Albrecht Dürer, Young Hare, 1502"
                class="poles-img"
              />
              <p class="poles-img-caption">Albrecht Dürer — <em>Young Hare</em>, 1502</p>
            </div>
            <div class="poles-card-text">
              <h3 class="poles-pole-name">Close to the visible world</h3>
              <p>The work refers directly to recognizable things. Dürer's hare is so precisely observed it functions almost as evidence—the visible world reproduced with enough fidelity that the viewer's eye has something specific to hold.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="poles-card">
            <div class="poles-img-wrap">
              <img
                src="/images/poles/1920px-Kandinsky_-_Composition_8,_July_1923.jpg"
                alt="Wassily Kandinsky, Composition VIII, 1923"
                class="poles-img"
              />
              <p class="poles-img-caption">Wassily Kandinsky — <em>Composition VIII</em>, 1923</p>
            </div>
            <div class="poles-card-text">
              <h3 class="poles-pole-name">Moved away from it</h3>
              <p>The work has left depiction behind. Kandinsky's compositions don't refer to things—they generate forces, tensions, and rhythms that the eye tracks without anchoring to the visible world. What's depicted is the experience itself.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <p>Art Lab doesn't tell you which position to take. It tells you which position you're actually in—and whether that's the one you meant to be in.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="poles-back">
      <a href="/hidden-grammar" class="hg-btn hg-btn--ghost">← Back to Art Lab</a>
    </div>

  </div>
</HiddenGrammarLayout>

<style>
  .poles-page {
    max-width: 800px;
  }

  .poles-header {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 1.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
  }

  .poles-eyebrow {
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #94a3b8;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;
  }

  .poles-header h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 4vw, 2.25rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: #1e293b;
    margin: 0 0 0.625rem 0;
    line-height: 1.2;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  .poles-subtitle {
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    color: #64748b;
    margin: 0;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .poles-body {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }

  .poles-body > p {
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    color: #374151;
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Axis sections */
  .poles-axis {
    background: #f8fafc;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-radius: 16px;
    padding: 1.75rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }

  .poles-axis-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #4f46e5;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .poles-axis-desc {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: #64748b;
    margin: 0;
    line-height: 1.6;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* Pole pair grid */
  .poles-pair {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .poles-card {
    background: #ffffff;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-radius: 12px;
    overflow: hidden;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  /* Images */
  .poles-img-wrap {
    border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    background: #f2f2f2;
  }

  .poles-img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    object-fit: contain;
    background: #f2f2f2;
  }

  .poles-img-caption {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: #94a3b8;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
  }

  .poles-img-caption em {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* Card text */
  .poles-card-text {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    flex: 1;
  }

  .poles-pole-name {
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #1e293b;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .poles-card-text p {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: #475569;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Back */
  .poles-back {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
  }

  /* Mobile */
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .poles-pair {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .poles-axis {
      padding: 1.25rem;
    }
  }
</style>
